params.markdown:
# Users

In IDM Suite, a user is a person who is using the product. They have an id and they log into the product with that ID.

The user dashboard is designed to inform people about what users are experiencing.
* What pages are they visiting?
* What actions are they undertaking?
* What is the performance they are experiencing?
* What kind of issues are they encountering?

attributes.title: [Filebeat Hitachi ID Bravura Monitor] Database: Search: Help

params.markdown:
Search engines need to return quickly since users are waiting on their results. There is a direct correlation between search time and user experience.

As a general rule, Search stored procedures should take less than a second to run on average.

Search stored procedure performance is impacted by elements such as:

* Data size. Larger data consumes more CPU, Ram, Disk I/O on the database server.
* Policies such as acls, filtering, etc.
* Indexes. Sometimes they fragment degrading overall performance.
* Table/Index Locking with other database actions.

Strategies for improving database search performance include:

* Rebuild fragmented database indexes.
* Evaluate if more RAM/CPU\When these don't work, Developers will need database execution plans to review options.

[Filebeat Hitachi ID Bravura Monitor] Database: Discovery: Help

params.markdown:
Discovery stored procedures are involved with loading data from integrations ( Connectors and LWS ) into the product database to learn about changes in the environment we are managing Identities and Access in.

Some general rules of thumbs:

* LWS stored procdures need to be quick. None should take a second.
* Iddiscover.exe stored procedures can run for much longer. Minutes to hours in large environments to process large changes in bulk.

Strategies for improving the performance of these stored procedures include:

* Rebuild fragmented database indexes
* Review if database is low on RAM, CPU, or I/O bandwidth.

If  you continue to encounter problems developers will require database execution plans to review the operation of these procedures.
